Whether the peace faithfully offered by all the Spaniards should be accepted, and whether peace should be granted unreservedly to all the Spaniards, by the whole Abiponian nation, these were the subjects of deliberation in that savage conclave. At first, there was a great diversity of opinions. Many inclined towards according their friendship to the inhabitants of Sta. Fe, Cordoba, and St. Iago, to the exclusion of the Corrientines and Para- guayrianS, denying the expediency of a uni- versal peace which should embrace all the Spaniards. “ Such a cessation,’' said they, “will cause the use of arms, and our ancient boast of military glory, to decay amongst us, Inac- tivity will destroy the love of war implanted in the youth of our nation. Grown effeminate like the pedestrian Indians, we shall be sub- jugated by the Spaniards, as soon as we cease to be formidable to them. War with one Spanish province at least is necessary to us, that we may still eujoy the opportunity of plundering those things of which we have need for daily use. We shall get. more from the Spaniards as their enemies, than as their friends.
